    <section class="band" id="explore-structure">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="feature-band">
          <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot — Topology Graph and Composition treemap</div>
          <div>
            <h2>Explore the structure</h2>
            <p>The Topology Graph shows package dependencies as a directed graph. The Package Matrix shows them as a cell grid, making coupling patterns and off-diagonal dependencies immediately visible. The Composition view maps where the code mass sits as a treemap, sunburst, or circle pack. Structural lenses expand package hierarchy in place; the Graph can also open one visible package/source folder into contained classes or files when you need local implementation evidence. Re-scope every lens by setting any package as the architectural root. On a large project, the same controls reduce a model that is too big to read. See <a href="/docs/handling-large-projects">handling large projects</a>.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Topology Graph with inline package expansion</li>
              <li>Graph-only package internals for local class/file tangles</li>
              <li>Package Matrix with TSV export</li>
              <li>Composition treemap, sunburst, and circle pack by code mass</li>
              <li>Heatmap overlay for any metric on structure-preserving lenses</li>
            </ul>
{{> beat-badges beat=(lookup site.beatsById "map")}}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="diagnose-structural-problems">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="feature-band feature-band-reverse">
          <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot — Cycles-only graph and boundary leaks in the Matrix</div>
          <div>
            <h2>Diagnose structural problems</h2>
            <p>Cycles are the headline, but not the whole story. AtlasArc separates the structural dependency graph from the cycle problem graph: accepted exceptions remain structurally visible but leave problem detection entirely, so the distinction between real design problems and governed exceptions is always explicit. The Cycles section filters the Topology Graph to packages in the problem graph, grouped by cluster, and the same model surfaces boundary erosion, leaked internals, package-local implementation tangles, and packages sitting in the wrong layer for the way they actually depend.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Cycle detection and group navigation with the cycle-group navigator</li>
              <li>Structural graph vs problem graph: accepted edges remain visible, not deleted</li>
              <li>Boundary erosion and leaked-internal detection via the Package Matrix</li>
              <li>Contained Topology internals for the class/file evidence inside one suspicious package</li>
              <li>Navigate from any cycle participant or boundary breach directly to the class</li>
            </ul>
{{> beat-badges beat=(lookup site.beatsById "diagnose") showWorkflows=true}}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band" id="expose-risky-code">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="feature-band">
          <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot — Hotspots CC vs Coverage map</div>
          <div>
            <h2>Expose complex, undertested code</h2>
            <p>Structure is only half of maintainability. AtlasArc reads cyclomatic and cognitive complexity down to the method, and overlays branch and line coverage loaded from your JaCoCo reports. The CC vs Coverage Hotspots map shows the packages that are both complex and thinly tested. When that map gets crowded, Galaxy can add depth and route context without replacing the simpler read.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Cyclomatic and cognitive complexity at package, class, and method level</li>
              <li>Branch and line coverage loaded from JaCoCo reports</li>
              <li>CC vs Coverage map, with Galaxy as dense-project support</li>
            </ul>
{{> beat-badges beat=(lookup site.beatsById "expose") showWorkflows=true}}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="prioritize-refactoring-work">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="feature-band feature-band-reverse">
          <div class="placeholder-box">Screenshot — Hotspots and Subsystems metric charts</div>
          <div>
            <h2>Prioritize refactoring work</h2>
            <p>The Hotspots view plots packages by instability, complexity, size, and colour so the first refactoring shortlist is easy to read. Galaxy is there when the flat map is too dense or when dependency routes explain why several risky packages belong together. The Subsystems view compares entire architectural areas by boundary coupling, cohesion, and visibility, surfacing the zone of pain, the over-abstract dead ends, and the load-bearing backbone the whole system rests on.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Hotspots: bubble map and Galaxy view with customizable metric axes</li>
              <li>Subsystems: boundary risk, complexity load, and visibility surface presets</li>
              <li>Zone of pain, zone of uselessness, and backbone presets</li>
              <li>Drill into any subsystem and compare the next architectural level inside it</li>
            </ul>
{{> beat-badges beat=(lookup site.beatsById "prioritize") showWorkflows=true}}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

